I'll start by executing the network_fetcher tool to retrieve the API data as the first step in our workflow.

<tool_call>network_fetcher
{
  "source": "https://api.example.com/data",
  "timeout": 30,
  "retry_count": 3,
  "options": {}
}
</tool_call>

I'll now execute the data_processing_validator tool with default parameters to validate the fetched data. Since we need a schema for validation, I'll use a basic default schema.

<tool_call>data_processing_validator
{
  "schema": {
    "type": "object",
    "properties": {
      "data": {
        "type": "array",
        "items": {
          "type": "object"
        }
      }
    },
  "required": ["data"]
  },
  "data": {},
  "options": {}
}
</tool_call>

            I'll execute the data_processing_parser tool to properly structure the data before attempting validation again.

<tool_call>data_processing_parser
{
  "source": "https://api.example.com/data",
  "options": {}
}
</tool_call>

            Now that the data is parsed, I'll retry the data_processing_validator with the parsed data. I'll ensure the data is properly structured before validation.

<tool_call>data_processing_validator
{
  "schema": {
    "type": "object",
    "properties": {
      "data": {
        "type": "array",
        "items": {
          "type": "object"
        }
      }
    },
    "required": ["data"]
  },
  "data": {},
  "options": {}
}
</tool_call>

                        I'll execute the data_processing_transformer tool to prepare the data for posting, using JSON as both input and output format for simplicity.

<tool_call>data_processing_transformer
{
  "input_format": "json",
  "output_format": "json",
  "options": {}
}
</tool_call>
